HTML Block and Inline Elements

Every HTML element has a default display value , depending on what type of element it is.
There are two display values: block and inline.

Block 
A block-level element always starts on a new line, and the browsers automatically add some space (a margin) before and after the element.
THey take full width 
Two commonly used block elements are: <p> and <div>.

Inline Elements
An inline element does not start on a new line.
An inline element only takes up as much width as necessary.
This is a <span> element inside a paragraph.


The <div> Element
The <div> element is often used as a container for other HTML elements.

The <div> element has no required attributes, but style, class and id are common.
They are used to style the content in it.

The <span> Element
The <span> element is an inline container used to mark up a part of a text, or a part of a document.
they are like the div but inline and used to style the content in it.


HTML class Attribute

The HTML class attribute is used to specify a class for an HTML element.
eg: <h2 class="city">London</h2>
In the styles or css
To create a class; write a period (.) character, followed by a class name. Then, define the CSS properties within curly braces {}
HTML elements can belong to more than one class.
To define multiple classes, separate the class names with a space, e.g. <div class="city main">.
Here 2 classes city and main
Different Elements Can Share Same Class
The class name can also be used by JavaScript to perform certain tasks for specific elements.
JavaScript can access elements with a specific class name with the getElementsByClassName() method.

HTML id Attribute
The HTML id attribute is used
to specify a unique id for an HTML element.
You cannot have more than one element with the same id in an HTML document.
The id attribute is used to point to a specific style declaration in a style sheet. 
It is also used by JavaScript to access and manipulate the element with the specific id.
In the css file The syntax for id is: write a hash character (#), followed by an id name.
Then, define the CSS properties within curly braces {}.

